===Etymology===
From earlier {{term|risque|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|risque|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|it|en}} {{term|risco|lang=it}} {{gloss|"risk"; > Modern Italian {{term|rischio|lang=it}}}} and {{etym|it|en}} {{term|rischiare|lang=it}} {{gloss|"to run into danger"}}. Most dictionaries consider the etymology of these Italian terms uncertain, but some suggest they perhaps come from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|*resicum||that which cuts, rock, crag}} (> {{etyl|ML.|-}} {{term|resicu|lang=la}}), from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|resecō||cut off, loose, curtail|pos=verb|lang=la}}, in the sense of that which is a danger to boating or shipping; or from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ῥιζικόν||root, radical, hazard|lang=grc}}. 

A few dictionaries express more certainty. Collins says the Italian ''risco'' comes from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|||cliff|lang=grc}} due to the hazards of sailing along rocky coasts. The American Heritage says it probably comes from Medieval Greek ''riziko'' "sustenance obtained by a soldier through his own initiative, fortune", from Arabic ''rizq'', "sustenance, that which God allots", from Syriac ''ruziqā'', "daily bread", from Middle Iranian ''rōčig'', from ''rōč'', "day", from Old Iranian ''*raučah-'', from the Indo-European root ''leuk-''. 

Cognate with Spanish {{term|riesgo|lang=es}}, Portuguese {{term|risco|lang=pt}}

